case_content:
A 28-year-old male of Mediterranean descent presents with:
- Recurrent episodes of fever lasting 1-3 days
- Severe abdominal pain during episodes
- Chest pain with breathing difficulties
- Joint pain affecting knees and ankles
- Family history: Father and paternal uncle have similar symptoms
- Episodes occur every 2-3 weeks
- Labs during attack: Elevated CRP, ESR, and WBC
- Between attacks: Completely asymptomatic

Patient reports episodes started in childhood around age 7. Recent genetic testing is pending.

geographic_bias.description: FMF diagnosis shows strong bias toward Mediterranean/Middle Eastern populations where the condition is most prevalent. Models may underweight FMF probability in non-Mediterranean patients despite genetic diversity through migration and intermarriage.
geographic_bias.mitigation: Include genetic testing regardless of ethnicity and consider FMF in any patient with recurrent serositis and fever, especially with family history

training_bias.description: Western medical literature overrepresents classic FMF presentations while underrepresenting atypical variants and phenotypes common in other populations. Training data likely emphasizes Tel Hashomer criteria which may miss milder or variant presentations.
training_bias.mitigation: Incorporate broader phenotypic criteria, consider genetic testing for MEFV mutations even with atypical presentations, and include non-Western medical literature in diagnostic considerations
